\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{rllllc}
\toprule
\# & Mass varied & Scale $\mu_q$ & $m_q(\mu_q)$ [GeV] & $Q(c,b,t)$ & residual vs $2/3$ \\
\midrule
1 & charm  & $m_c(m_c) = 1.281$~GeV & $1.28070$ & $0.6620198$ & $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
2 & charm  & $m_\tau = 1.777$~GeV   & $1.14262$ & $0.6667177$ & $\mathbf{+5.10 \times 10^{-5}}$ \\
3 & charm  & $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.883$~GeV & $1.12304$ & $0.6674137$ & $+7.47 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
\midrule
4 & bottom & $m_b(m_b) = 4.203$~GeV & $4.20300$ & $0.6620198$ & $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
5 & bottom & $M_W = 80.369$~GeV     & $2.91351$ & $0.6861892$ & $+1.95 \times 10^{-2}$ \\
6 & bottom & $M_Z = 91.188$~GeV     & $2.88175$ & $0.6868807$ & $+2.02 \times 10^{-2}$ \\
7 & bottom & $m_H = 125.25$~GeV     & $2.80627$ & $0.6885464$ & $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$ \\
\midrule
8 & top    & $m_t(m_t) = 162.5$~GeV & $162.500$ & $0.6620198$ & $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{All eight trials in the constrained search space defined by the rule of Section~\ref{sec:rule}. For each trial, one of the three heavy quark masses is varied from its self-scale to a Standard Model particle scale within its perturbative running window; the other two masses are held at their respective self-scales. Trials 1, 4, and 8 are degenerate (all-self-scales) and produce identical results; we count them as three trials for transparency, even though they are the same calculation. Of the eight trials, one (trial \#2, charm at $m_\tau$) closes to within $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ of $2/3$. The other seven produce residuals between $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ and $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$, between two and three orders of magnitude farther from closure than trial \#2. Computed by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_constrained\_search.py} in the accompanying repository \citep{RepoHeavy}.}
\label{tab:eight_trials}
\end{table}

\paragraph{The closure direction matches the literature direction.} The all-self-scales evaluation (trial \#1 / \#4 / \#8) gives a residual of $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$. To close the relation, $Q$ must increase. Of the seven non-self-scale trials, only the three charm trials are candidates to move $Q$ in the required direction (the four bottom trials and the one degenerate top trial all either move it the wrong way or leave it unchanged). Among the three charm trials, only the $m_\tau$ trial brings the residual within an order of magnitude of $\sigma_Q$. The two non-self-scale charm trials at $m_\tau$ and $\Sigma m_\ell$ produce residuals of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ and $+7.47 \times 10^{-4}$ respectively: both have moved $Q$ in the required direction (residual sign-flipped from negative to positive), but the $m_\tau$ trial overshoots the target by $\sim 15\times$ less than the $\Sigma m_\ell$ trial.

\paragraph{The bottom-at-boson trials all move $Q$ in the wrong direction.} Trials \#5, \#6, \#7 (bottom at $M_W$, $M_Z$, $m_H$) all produce residuals between $+1.95 \times 10^{-2}$ and $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$, three orders of magnitude further from $2/3$ than the all-self-scales baseline. The reason is mechanical: running $m_b$ upward from its self-scale of $4.20$~GeV to a boson scale near or above $80$~GeV reduces $m_b(\mu)$ from $4.20$ to approximately $2.85$~GeV, a fractional shift of $-32\%$. This pushes $Q$ further from $2/3$, in the opposite direction from what the literature direction requires. None of the four bottom trials is a candidate for closure on direction grounds alone, and the calculation confirms this.


\section{Uncertainty Budget at the $m_\tau$ Trial}
\label{sec:budget}

We propagate each input uncertainty independently through the four-loop running and Koide combination to obtain the contribution of each source to $\sigma_Q$ at the $m_\tau$ trial. Table~\ref{tab:budget} shows the decomposition.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution to $Q$ & Fraction of total variance \\
\midrule
FLAG $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV & $4.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & 0.65\% \\
FLAG $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV   & $1.82 \times 10^{-4}$ & 12.8\% \\
PDG $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV       & $4.73 \times 10^{-4}$ & 86.4\% \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$       & $1.78 \times 10^{-4}$ & (separate)  \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum (quark masses + $\alpha_s$) & $5.39 \times 10^{-4}$ & \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Decomposition of $\sigma_Q$ at $\mu_c = m_\tau$ under independent variation of each input. The PDG uncertainty on $m_t$ dominates the budget, contributing approximately $86\%$ of the variance. The FLAG uncertainty on $m_c(m_c)$ --- the only mass whose evaluation scale is being varied --- contributes less than $1\%$ of the total. Input correlations among $m_c$, $m_b$, $m_t$, and $\alpha_s$ from shared lattice and scheme-conversion systematics are not propagated; the quadrature sum assumes independent Gaussian errors and is a standard approximation.}
\label{tab:budget}
\end{table}

The total propagated uncertainty is $\sigma_Q \approx 5.39 \times 10^{-4}$. The observed residual at the $m_\tau$ trial is $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, approximately a factor of ten smaller than $\sigma_Q$. We note explicitly that this is a measurement-precision statement: a residual smaller than $\sigma_Q$ is consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$, and is also consistent with any other value within the propagated band.


\section{Test of Mixed-Sector Triples: A Null Result}
\label{sec:mixed_sector}

The lepton-scale hypothesis raised in Section~\ref{sec:intro} predicts that lepton-derived scales may enter quark-sector relations. The constrained-search test of Section~\ref{sec:trials} found one closure of the heavy $(c, b, t)$ Koide combination at $\mu_c = m_\tau$. To test whether the phenomenon extends to mixed-sector Koide-form triples that algebraically interleave leptons and quarks, we additionally evaluated $Q$ for every triple of the form $(\ell_1, \ell_2, q)$ and $(\ell, q_1, q_2)$ where $\ell_i$ are charged leptons (at pole mass) and $q_i$ are quarks (at one of three lepton-derived evaluation scales: $m_\tau$, $\Sigma m_\ell$, $m_\mu$). The full enumeration produces $54$ trials.

The result is straightforward. \textbf{No mixed-sector triple closes.} The best of the $54$ has residual $+1.67 \times 10^{-3}$ from the nearest small rational, approximately $30\times$ farther from any rational closure than the $(c, b, t)$ at $m_\tau$ trial. The full $54$-trial table is in the accompanying repository (\texttt{heavy\_koide\_mixed\_sector\_scan.py}); the top five entries are reproduced in Table~\ref{tab:mixed_sector_top5} for reference.

