\paragraph{Implication.} The lepton-scale phenomenon, to the extent it is real, is not a generic feature of mixed-sector Koide combinations. The two anomalously-tight numerical observations across the present work and the companion note --- the lepton-Soddy match to $m_s$ at $\Sigma m_\ell$, and the $(c, b, t)$ Koide closure with $m_c$ run to $m_\tau$ --- both involve lepton-derived scales entering quark-sector relations, but they appear in distinct algebraic forms (Soddy/Descartes geometry in one case, Koide algebra in the other) and do not extend to the more naive mixed-sector Koide variants. We report the null on the broader extension as a constraint on any future theoretical interpretation: any mechanism proposed to explain the observed pattern must account for both the existence of the two specific closures and the absence of closures in the $54$ broader extensions.


\section{Caveats}
\label{sec:caveats}

We make the following limitations explicit.

\paragraph{The closure is conditioned on the specific within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription.} Trial \#2 of Table~\ref{tab:eight_trials} corresponds to one specific arrangement of evaluation scales within $\overline{\text{MS}}$. We have demonstrated in Section~\ref{sec:trials} that the closure does not occur at any other prescription in the constrained trial space, and in Section~\ref{sec:rule} that the common-scale prescription is mathematically excluded. The closure is real within the rule, but it is conditioned on the rule: a different rule (e.g., admitting round-number reference scales like $2$~GeV, or admitting prescriptions in which two masses simultaneously deviate from their self-scales) would produce a different and larger trial space.

\paragraph{The residual lies within input uncertainty.} The residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ at trial \#2 is approximately $1/10$ of the propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q$. This means the observed value of $Q$ is consistent with $2/3$ exactly, but is also consistent with any other value within $\sigma_Q$. We do not claim the relation is exact; we report the closure as a numerical observation and decline to interpret the consistency level as a significance statement.

\paragraph{Not a derivation, mechanism, or prediction.} We have not derived the relation from a Lagrangian, symmetry, or first-principles framework. We do not propose a mechanism that would generate the closure. The relation is post-hoc in the sense that all input masses were measured before the calculation. We do not derive why $\mu_c = m_\tau$ specifically; the rule of Section~\ref{sec:rule} admits three charm trials and we report the result for all three.

\paragraph{$\overline{\text{MS}}$-specific.} The result is conditioned on the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme. Robustness across alternative renormalon-improved heavy-quark mass schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) has not been tested in this paper and is left to future work.


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Two observations, one hypothesis.} The companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported a Soddy/Descartes geometric construction in which the squared outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple matches $m_s$ at $\Sigma m_\ell$. The present paper reports a Koide algebraic closure of the heavy $(c, b, t)$ triple with $m_c$ evaluated at $m_\tau$. The two observations involve different mathematical operations (Soddy curvature versus Koide combination), different quark masses ($m_s$ versus $m_c$ within a heavy triple), and different lepton-derived scales ($\Sigma m_\ell$ versus $m_\tau$). They share the common feature that a lepton-derived scale enters the characterization of a quark-sector quantity.

This common feature was the working hypothesis tested in the present paper. The constrained search of Section~\ref{sec:trials} found exactly one closure in eight trials, in the direction predicted by the literature near-miss. The mixed-sector null of Section~\ref{sec:mixed_sector} found that the phenomenon does not generically extend to algebraically interleaved lepton-quark Koide variants. The observed pattern is therefore narrow: two specific structural conditions, in two distinct algebraic forms, neither of which generalizes to nearby mixed-sector constructions.

\paragraph{What this allows future work to investigate.} The narrow scope of the observed pattern is, in our view, more useful as a constraint than a broader pattern would be. Any theoretical framework that attempts to explain why lepton-derived scales appear in quark-sector relations must reproduce two specific facts: (i)~the lepton-Soddy/$m_s$ match at $\Sigma m_\ell$, and (ii)~the heavy-Koide $(c, b, t)$ closure at $\mu_c = m_\tau$, and must also explain (iii)~why the $54$ tested mixed-sector variants do not close. A mechanism that produces (i) and (ii) but predicts a sea of additional closures is ruled out by (iii); a mechanism that predicts only (i) or only (ii) is incomplete.

\paragraph{Falsification path.} The observation will be sharpened or excluded by improvements to two inputs: (a)~the precision on $m_t^{\overline{\text{MS}}}$, currently dominating $\sigma_Q$ at $86\%$ of the variance, and (b)~independent lattice or analytical computations of the heavy-quark Koide combination at higher precision than the present four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running. If a future improved measurement of $m_t$ moves the central residual outside the shrinking $\sigma_Q$ band, the closure is excluded at the corresponding confidence; if it remains within the band, the situation is unchanged in interpretation but more sharply characterized numerically.


\section*{Computational Note}

All computations are reproducible from the accompanying GitHub repository \citep{RepoHeavy}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running is performed via \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$. The eight constrained-search trials of Section~\ref{sec:trials} are computed by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_constrained\_search.py}. The $54$ mixed-sector trials of Section~\ref{sec:mixed_sector} are computed by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_mixed\_sector\_scan.py}. All input values are PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} and FLAG 2024 \citep{FLAG2024} central values at the time of computation. Total runtime is approximately one minute on a laptop.


