\documentclass[11pt,a4paper]{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb,amsthm}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{booktabs}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage[margin=1in]{geometry}
\usepackage{natbib}

\title{A Constrained-Search Test of the Lepton-Scale Hypothesis on the $(c, b, t)$ Heavy Koide Combination}
\author{Andrew M.~Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 14, 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m)/(\sum \sqrt{m})^2 = 2/3$ holds for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}. Extensions to the quark sector \citep{Rivero2011} have noted that the heavy triple $(c, b, t)$ in $\overline{\text{MS}}$ at all-self-scales sits at a residual of $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ from $2/3$, a known near-miss with sign indicating that $Q$ needs to increase to close. In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported a numerical observation in which a lepton-derived scale ($\Sigma m_\ell$) enters the characterization of the strange-quark mass via a Soddy/Descartes geometric construction, suggesting a working hypothesis: lepton-derived scales may enter quark-sector relations under specific structural conditions.

The present note reports a constrained-search test of that hypothesis on the heavy $(c, b, t)$ Koide combination. We adopt a search rule which is, by direct count, more restrictive than the conventional phenomenological alternatives: each heavy quark mass may be evaluated either at its own self-scale or at the mass of any Standard Model particle that lies within that quark's perturbative running window. We prove that under this rule the search space contains exactly eight trials, distributed as one for top, four for bottom, and three for charm, and we prove that the common-scale prescription is mathematically excluded by the non-overlap of the three running windows (top's lower bound exceeds charm's upper bound). All eight trials are computed and reported.

The result: of the eight trials, one closes. The combination $Q(c, b, t)$ with $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their tabulation self-scales and $m_c$ run via four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ to $\mu = m_\tau$ takes the value $0.666718$ against $2/3 = 0.666667$, a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$. The propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q$ is approximately $5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, dominated by the PDG uncertainty on $m_t$. The closure is approximately one order of magnitude below the input-precision band. The closure direction matches the literature near-miss direction (residual moves from $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ to $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, a sign change of the expected sense). The other seven trials --- charm at self-scale, charm at $\Sigma m_\ell$, bottom at self-scale, bottom at $M_W$, bottom at $M_Z$, bottom at $m_H$, and top at self-scale --- produce residuals between $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ and $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$, two to three orders of magnitude away from closure.

To test whether the lepton-scale phenomenon extends to mixed-sector triples that algebraically interleave leptons and quarks, we additionally evaluated the Koide combination over $54$ such triples (every $(\ell_1, \ell_2, q)$ and $(\ell, q_1, q_2)$ combination with the quark masses evaluated at lepton-derived scales). \textbf{No mixed-sector triple closes.} The best of the $54$ has residual $+1.67 \times 10^{-3}$ against the nearest small rational, approximately $30\times$ farther from closure than the $(c, b, t)$ at $m_\tau$ result. The lepton-scale phenomenon is therefore not a generic feature of mixed-sector Koide combinations: it appears narrowly, at specific structural conditions, in two distinct forms across the present work and the companion note.

\smallskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Koide relation; heavy quark masses; constrained search; lepton-derived scales; numerical observation
\end{abstract}


\section{Background and Motivation}
\label{sec:intro}

The Koide relation \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide_lepton}
\end{equation}
holds for the charged lepton pole masses to a residual of $-6.16 \times 10^{-6}$, an empirical regularity for which no derivation is currently accepted. Extensions to the quark sector were initiated by Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} for the $(s, c, b)$ triple under a $-\sqrt{m_s}$ sign convention. The natural sign-positive heavy triple $(c, b, t)$, computed with all three masses at their respective $\overline{\text{MS}}$ self-scales (the standard tabulation convention used by FLAG \citep{FLAG2024} and PDG \citep{PDG2024}), gives
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\text{all self-scales}} \;=\; 0.6620198, \qquad \text{residual} \;=\; -4.65 \times 10^{-3},
\end{equation}
a known near-miss whose direction (residual negative, $Q$ below $2/3$) indicates that for the combination to close, $Q$ must increase. We refer to this throughout as the \emph{literature direction}: the sign of the required correction is determined by the published all-self-scales evaluation, not by exploration.

In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported that the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating charged-lepton Descartes configuration matches the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau \approx 1883$~MeV within current FLAG lattice precision. That observation involves a lepton-derived quantity matching a quark mass at a lepton-derived scale, and it raised a working hypothesis: \textbf{lepton-derived scales may enter quark-sector relations under specific structural conditions}. The present note tests this hypothesis on an independent quark-sector object --- the heavy Koide combination --- using a search procedure constructed before the calculation to satisfy three properties: it is enumerable, it is more restricted than conventional phenomenological scale choices, and the candidate set is determined mechanically rather than by author selection.

\section{Setup}
\label{sec:setup}

We work in the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme throughout. Inputs:

\begin{itemize}
\item $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$, \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$, \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV ($\overline{\text{MS}}$, derived from PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} $m_t^{\text{pole}} = 172.57 \pm 0.29$~GeV via the four-loop pole-to-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ conversion of \citep{Marquard2015} as implemented in \texttt{CRunDec})
\item $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ \citep{PDG2024}
\item $m_e = 0.5109989461$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6583755$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV \citep{PDG2024}
\item $M_W = 80.369$~GeV, $M_Z = 91.1876$~GeV, $m_H = 125.25$~GeV \citep{PDG2024}
\end{itemize}

All quark masses are $\overline{\text{MS}}$ throughout: a single mass-renormalization scheme, no mixing of schemes. The three masses are evaluated at three different RG points within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, the standard PDG/FLAG tabulation convention. Running between scales is performed via four-loop QCD using \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec}, with full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$ giving active-flavor regions $n_f \in \{3, 4, 5, 6\}$. The combination is
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)(\mu_c, \mu_b, \mu_t) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_c(\mu_c) + m_b(\mu_b) + m_t(\mu_t)}{\left(\sqrt{m_c(\mu_c)} + \sqrt{m_b(\mu_b)} + \sqrt{m_t(\mu_t)}\right)^2}.
\label{eq:Q_def}
\end{equation}
where $\mu_q$ is the RG point at which $m_q$ is evaluated within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.


\section{The Constrained-Search Rule and Trial Space}
\label{sec:rule}

\subsection{The rule}

We adopt the following search rule, stated before the calculation:
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Rule.} The RG point $\mu_q$ at which a heavy quark mass $m_q$ is evaluated within $\overline{\text{MS}}$ must be either (i)~the self-scale $m_q(m_q)$ of that quark, or (ii)~the mass of a Standard Model particle that lies within the perturbative running window of $m_q$.
\end{quote}
The perturbative running window of a heavy quark mass $m_q$ is the interval bounded by adjacent flavor thresholds: $[m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b)]$ for charm in the $n_f = 4$ region, $[m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)]$ for bottom in the $n_f = 5$ region, and $[m_t(m_t), \infty)$ for top in the $n_f = 6$ region. We require Standard Model particle scales (fermion or boson masses) and explicitly disallow round-number conventions ($1.5$~GeV, $2$~GeV, $\ldots$) which are tabulation conveniences rather than physical scales.

\subsection{Enumeration of the trial space}

Under this rule, we enumerate the trial space directly:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Top.} Running window $[m_t(m_t), \infty)$. No Standard Model particle has rest mass above $m_t$. Trial count for top: \textbf{one} (self-scale only).
\item \textbf{Bottom.} Running window $[m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)] = [4.20, 162.5]$~GeV. Standard Model particles in this window: $M_W = 80.369$~GeV, $M_Z = 91.188$~GeV, $m_H = 125.25$~GeV, plus the self-scale itself. Trial count for bottom: \textbf{four}.
\item \textbf{Charm.} Running window $[m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b)] = [1.28, 4.20]$~GeV. Standard Model particles in this window: $m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV and $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.88303$~GeV (the charged-lepton sum), plus the self-scale itself. Trial count for charm: \textbf{three}.
\end{itemize}

We test trials in which a single mass is varied from its self-scale to a candidate scale in its window; the other two masses are held at their respective self-scales. Total trial count: $\mathbf{1 + 4 + 3 = 8}$.

\subsection{Proof that the trial space is more restricted than the conventional phenomenological space}

\begin{proposition}
Let $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ denote the trial space defined above. Let $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$ denote the conventional phenomenological scale space, in which each heavy quark mass may be evaluated independently at any of the standard reference scales used in the heavy-quark mass literature: $\{m_c(m_c), 1.5 \mathrm{~GeV}, 2 \mathrm{~GeV}, m_b(m_b), m_\tau, \Sigma m_\ell, M_W, M_Z, m_H, m_t(m_t)\}$, ten options per mass. Then
\begin{equation}
|\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}| = 8 \;\;<\;\; |\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}| = 10^3 = 1000.
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
$|\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}| = 8$ by direct enumeration above. For $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$, each of the three masses may independently take any of ten scale values, giving $10^3 = 1000$ prescriptions. Containment $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}} \subset \mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$ holds trivially: every prescription in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ is also in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$, since (i) every running-window scale used in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ appears in the conventional list, and (ii) the constraint that at most one mass deviates from its self-scale is a strict additional restriction not imposed in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$. The containment is strict because, e.g., $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$ admits the prescription $(\mu_c = 2 \mathrm{~GeV}, \mu_b = m_b, \mu_t = m_t)$ which is not in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ ($2$~GeV is a tabulation convention, not a particle mass). \qed
\end{proof}

The trial space of this paper is therefore $125\times$ smaller than the conventional phenomenological space. The corresponding Bonferroni penalty is $8$, not $1000$.

\subsection{Proof that the common-scale prescription is mathematically excluded}

\begin{proposition}
There exists no scale $\mu \in \mathbb{R}_{>0}$ at which all three masses $m_c, m_b, m_t$ can be simultaneously evaluated within their respective perturbative running windows.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The three perturbative running windows are
\begin{align*}
W_c &= [m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b)] = [1.28, 4.20]~\text{GeV}, \\
W_b &= [m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)] = [4.20, 162.5]~\text{GeV}, \\
W_t &= [m_t(m_t), \infty) = [162.5, \infty)~\text{GeV}.
\end{align*}
A common scale $\mu$ for all three masses requires $\mu \in W_c \cap W_b \cap W_t$. We have $\sup W_c = 4.20$~GeV and $\inf W_t = 162.5$~GeV, with $4.20 < 162.5$, so $W_c \cap W_t = \emptyset$, and therefore $W_c \cap W_b \cap W_t = \emptyset$. \qed
\end{proof}

The common-scale prescription is therefore excluded by the non-overlap of the perturbative running windows, not by author choice. Empirically, if one extrapolates each mass outside its own perturbative window to a common $\mu$ (an unphysical procedure, since at least one mass is then evaluated outside the regime where its $\overline{\text{MS}}$ definition is reliable), the resulting combination $Q(c, b, t)$ is approximately constant at $0.7192$ across the entire perturbative range and never crosses $2/3$ at any scale. The common-scale extrapolation does not admit a closure even when permitted unphysically.


\section{Results: All Eight Trials}
\label{sec:trials}

We compute $Q(c, b, t)$ for each of the eight trials defined in Section~\ref{sec:rule}. Results are in Table~\ref{tab:eight_trials}.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{rllllc}
\toprule
\# & Mass varied & Scale $\mu_q$ & $m_q(\mu_q)$ [GeV] & $Q(c,b,t)$ & residual vs $2/3$ \\
\midrule
1 & charm  & $m_c(m_c) = 1.281$~GeV & $1.28070$ & $0.6620198$ & $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
2 & charm  & $m_\tau = 1.777$~GeV   & $1.14262$ & $0.6667177$ & $\mathbf{+5.10 \times 10^{-5}}$ \\
3 & charm  & $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.883$~GeV & $1.12304$ & $0.6674137$ & $+7.47 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
\midrule
4 & bottom & $m_b(m_b) = 4.203$~GeV & $4.20300$ & $0.6620198$ & $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
5 & bottom & $M_W = 80.369$~GeV     & $2.91351$ & $0.6861892$ & $+1.95 \times 10^{-2}$ \\
6 & bottom & $M_Z = 91.188$~GeV     & $2.88175$ & $0.6868807$ & $+2.02 \times 10^{-2}$ \\
7 & bottom & $m_H = 125.25$~GeV     & $2.80627$ & $0.6885464$ & $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$ \\
\midrule
8 & top    & $m_t(m_t) = 162.5$~GeV & $162.500$ & $0.6620198$ & $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{All eight trials in the constrained search space defined by the rule of Section~\ref{sec:rule}. For each trial, one of the three heavy quark masses is varied from its self-scale to a Standard Model particle scale within its perturbative running window; the other two masses are held at their respective self-scales. Trials 1, 4, and 8 are degenerate (all-self-scales) and produce identical results; we count them as three trials for transparency, even though they are the same calculation. Of the eight trials, one (trial \#2, charm at $m_\tau$) closes to within $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ of $2/3$. The other seven produce residuals between $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ and $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$, between two and three orders of magnitude farther from closure than trial \#2. Computed by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_constrained\_search.py} in the accompanying repository \citep{RepoHeavy}.}
\label{tab:eight_trials}
\end{table}

\paragraph{The closure direction matches the literature direction.} The all-self-scales evaluation (trial \#1 / \#4 / \#8) gives a residual of $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$. To close the relation, $Q$ must increase. Of the seven non-self-scale trials, only the three charm trials are candidates to move $Q$ in the required direction (the four bottom trials and the one degenerate top trial all either move it the wrong way or leave it unchanged). Among the three charm trials, only the $m_\tau$ trial brings the residual within an order of magnitude of $\sigma_Q$. The two non-self-scale charm trials at $m_\tau$ and $\Sigma m_\ell$ produce residuals of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ and $+7.47 \times 10^{-4}$ respectively: both have moved $Q$ in the required direction (residual sign-flipped from negative to positive), but the $m_\tau$ trial overshoots the target by $\sim 15\times$ less than the $\Sigma m_\ell$ trial.

\paragraph{The bottom-at-boson trials all move $Q$ in the wrong direction.} Trials \#5, \#6, \#7 (bottom at $M_W$, $M_Z$, $m_H$) all produce residuals between $+1.95 \times 10^{-2}$ and $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$, three orders of magnitude further from $2/3$ than the all-self-scales baseline. The reason is mechanical: running $m_b$ upward from its self-scale of $4.20$~GeV to a boson scale near or above $80$~GeV reduces $m_b(\mu)$ from $4.20$ to approximately $2.85$~GeV, a fractional shift of $-32\%$. This pushes $Q$ further from $2/3$, in the opposite direction from what the literature direction requires. None of the four bottom trials is a candidate for closure on direction grounds alone, and the calculation confirms this.


\section{Uncertainty Budget at the $m_\tau$ Trial}
\label{sec:budget}

We propagate each input uncertainty independently through the four-loop running and Koide combination to obtain the contribution of each source to $\sigma_Q$ at the $m_\tau$ trial. Table~\ref{tab:budget} shows the decomposition.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution to $Q$ & Fraction of total variance \\
\midrule
FLAG $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV & $4.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & 0.65\% \\
FLAG $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV   & $1.82 \times 10^{-4}$ & 12.8\% \\
PDG $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV       & $4.73 \times 10^{-4}$ & 86.4\% \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$       & $1.78 \times 10^{-4}$ & (separate)  \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum (quark masses + $\alpha_s$) & $5.39 \times 10^{-4}$ & \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Decomposition of $\sigma_Q$ at $\mu_c = m_\tau$ under independent variation of each input. The PDG uncertainty on $m_t$ dominates the budget, contributing approximately $86\%$ of the variance. The FLAG uncertainty on $m_c(m_c)$ --- the only mass whose evaluation scale is being varied --- contributes less than $1\%$ of the total. Input correlations among $m_c$, $m_b$, $m_t$, and $\alpha_s$ from shared lattice and scheme-conversion systematics are not propagated; the quadrature sum assumes independent Gaussian errors and is a standard approximation.}
\label{tab:budget}
\end{table}

The total propagated uncertainty is $\sigma_Q \approx 5.39 \times 10^{-4}$. The observed residual at the $m_\tau$ trial is $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, approximately a factor of ten smaller than $\sigma_Q$. We note explicitly that this is a measurement-precision statement: a residual smaller than $\sigma_Q$ is consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$, and is also consistent with any other value within the propagated band.


\section{Test of Mixed-Sector Triples: A Null Result}
\label{sec:mixed_sector}

The lepton-scale hypothesis raised in Section~\ref{sec:intro} predicts that lepton-derived scales may enter quark-sector relations. The constrained-search test of Section~\ref{sec:trials} found one closure of the heavy $(c, b, t)$ Koide combination at $\mu_c = m_\tau$. To test whether the phenomenon extends to mixed-sector Koide-form triples that algebraically interleave leptons and quarks, we additionally evaluated $Q$ for every triple of the form $(\ell_1, \ell_2, q)$ and $(\ell, q_1, q_2)$ where $\ell_i$ are charged leptons (at pole mass) and $q_i$ are quarks (at one of three lepton-derived evaluation scales: $m_\tau$, $\Sigma m_\ell$, $m_\mu$). The full enumeration produces $54$ trials.

The result is straightforward. \textbf{No mixed-sector triple closes.} The best of the $54$ has residual $+1.67 \times 10^{-3}$ from the nearest small rational, approximately $30\times$ farther from any rational closure than the $(c, b, t)$ at $m_\tau$ trial. The full $54$-trial table is in the accompanying repository (\texttt{heavy\_koide\_mixed\_sector\_scan.py}); the top five entries are reproduced in Table~\ref{tab:mixed_sector_top5} for reference.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{rllcll}
\toprule
\# & Triple & Quark scale & $Q$ & Best target & Residual \\
\midrule
1 & $(e, c, b)$    & $\Sigma m_\ell$ & $0.55722$ & $5/9 \approx 0.5556$ & $+1.67 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
2 & $(e, c, b)$    & $m_\tau$        & $0.55729$ & $5/9$                & $+1.73 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
3 & $(e, \mu, c)$  & $m_\tau$        & $0.62230$ & $5/8 = 0.625$        & $-2.70 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
4 & $(e, \tau, c)$ & $\Sigma m_\ell$ & $0.49717$ & $1/2$                & $-2.83 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
5 & $(e, \tau, c)$ & $m_\tau$        & $0.49674$ & $1/2$                & $-3.26 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Top five entries (smallest $|$residual$|$) from the $54$-trial mixed-sector scan. Column ``Best target'' shows the nearest small rational with denominator $\leq 18$. None of the $54$ trials achieves a residual smaller than $1.67 \times 10^{-3}$, which is approximately $30\times$ the residual of the $(c, b, t)$ at $m_\tau$ trial in Table~\ref{tab:eight_trials}. The full table is in the accompanying repository.}
\label{tab:mixed_sector_top5}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Implication.} The lepton-scale phenomenon, to the extent it is real, is not a generic feature of mixed-sector Koide combinations. The two anomalously-tight numerical observations across the present work and the companion note --- the lepton-Soddy match to $m_s$ at $\Sigma m_\ell$, and the $(c, b, t)$ Koide closure with $m_c$ run to $m_\tau$ --- both involve lepton-derived scales entering quark-sector relations, but they appear in distinct algebraic forms (Soddy/Descartes geometry in one case, Koide algebra in the other) and do not extend to the more naive mixed-sector Koide variants. We report the null on the broader extension as a constraint on any future theoretical interpretation: any mechanism proposed to explain the observed pattern must account for both the existence of the two specific closures and the absence of closures in the $54$ broader extensions.


\section{Caveats}
\label{sec:caveats}

We make the following limitations explicit.

\paragraph{The closure is conditioned on the specific within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription.} Trial \#2 of Table~\ref{tab:eight_trials} corresponds to one specific arrangement of evaluation scales within $\overline{\text{MS}}$. We have demonstrated in Section~\ref{sec:trials} that the closure does not occur at any other prescription in the constrained trial space, and in Section~\ref{sec:rule} that the common-scale prescription is mathematically excluded. The closure is real within the rule, but it is conditioned on the rule: a different rule (e.g., admitting round-number reference scales like $2$~GeV, or admitting prescriptions in which two masses simultaneously deviate from their self-scales) would produce a different and larger trial space.

\paragraph{The residual lies within input uncertainty.} The residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ at trial \#2 is approximately $1/10$ of the propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q$. This means the observed value of $Q$ is consistent with $2/3$ exactly, but is also consistent with any other value within $\sigma_Q$. We do not claim the relation is exact; we report the closure as a numerical observation and decline to interpret the consistency level as a significance statement.

\paragraph{Not a derivation, mechanism, or prediction.} We have not derived the relation from a Lagrangian, symmetry, or first-principles framework. We do not propose a mechanism that would generate the closure. The relation is post-hoc in the sense that all input masses were measured before the calculation. We do not derive why $\mu_c = m_\tau$ specifically; the rule of Section~\ref{sec:rule} admits three charm trials and we report the result for all three.

\paragraph{$\overline{\text{MS}}$-specific.} The result is conditioned on the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme. Robustness across alternative renormalon-improved heavy-quark mass schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) has not been tested in this paper and is left to future work.


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Two observations, one hypothesis.} The companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported a Soddy/Descartes geometric construction in which the squared outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple matches $m_s$ at $\Sigma m_\ell$. The present paper reports a Koide algebraic closure of the heavy $(c, b, t)$ triple with $m_c$ evaluated at $m_\tau$. The two observations involve different mathematical operations (Soddy curvature versus Koide combination), different quark masses ($m_s$ versus $m_c$ within a heavy triple), and different lepton-derived scales ($\Sigma m_\ell$ versus $m_\tau$). They share the common feature that a lepton-derived scale enters the characterization of a quark-sector quantity.

This common feature was the working hypothesis tested in the present paper. The constrained search of Section~\ref{sec:trials} found exactly one closure in eight trials, in the direction predicted by the literature near-miss. The mixed-sector null of Section~\ref{sec:mixed_sector} found that the phenomenon does not generically extend to algebraically interleaved lepton-quark Koide variants. The observed pattern is therefore narrow: two specific structural conditions, in two distinct algebraic forms, neither of which generalizes to nearby mixed-sector constructions.

\paragraph{What this allows future work to investigate.} The narrow scope of the observed pattern is, in our view, more useful as a constraint than a broader pattern would be. Any theoretical framework that attempts to explain why lepton-derived scales appear in quark-sector relations must reproduce two specific facts: (i)~the lepton-Soddy/$m_s$ match at $\Sigma m_\ell$, and (ii)~the heavy-Koide $(c, b, t)$ closure at $\mu_c = m_\tau$, and must also explain (iii)~why the $54$ tested mixed-sector variants do not close. A mechanism that produces (i) and (ii) but predicts a sea of additional closures is ruled out by (iii); a mechanism that predicts only (i) or only (ii) is incomplete.

\paragraph{Falsification path.} The observation will be sharpened or excluded by improvements to two inputs: (a)~the precision on $m_t^{\overline{\text{MS}}}$, currently dominating $\sigma_Q$ at $86\%$ of the variance, and (b)~independent lattice or analytical computations of the heavy-quark Koide combination at higher precision than the present four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running. If a future improved measurement of $m_t$ moves the central residual outside the shrinking $\sigma_Q$ band, the closure is excluded at the corresponding confidence; if it remains within the band, the situation is unchanged in interpretation but more sharply characterized numerically.


\section*{Computational Note}

All computations are reproducible from the accompanying GitHub repository \citep{RepoHeavy}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running is performed via \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$. The eight constrained-search trials of Section~\ref{sec:trials} are computed by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_constrained\_search.py}. The $54$ mixed-sector trials of Section~\ref{sec:mixed_sector} are computed by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_mixed\_sector\_scan.py}. All input values are PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} and FLAG 2024 \citep{FLAG2024} central values at the time of computation. Total runtime is approximately one minute on a laptop.


