\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m)/(\sum \sqrt{m})^2 = 2/3$ holds for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}. Extensions to the quark sector \citep{Rivero2011} have noted that the heavy triple $(c, b, t)$ in $\overline{\text{MS}}$ at all-self-scales sits at a residual of $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ from $2/3$, a known near-miss with sign indicating that $Q$ needs to increase to close. In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported a numerical observation in which a lepton-derived scale ($\Sigma m_\ell$) enters the characterization of the strange-quark mass via a Soddy/Descartes geometric construction, suggesting a working hypothesis: lepton-derived scales may enter quark-sector relations under specific structural conditions.

The present note reports a constrained-search test of that hypothesis on the heavy $(c, b, t)$ Koide combination. We adopt a search rule which is, by direct count, more restrictive than the conventional phenomenological alternatives: each heavy quark mass may be evaluated either at its own self-scale or at the mass of any Standard Model particle that lies within that quark's perturbative running window. We prove that under this rule the search space contains exactly eight trials, distributed as one for top, four for bottom, and three for charm, and we prove that the common-scale prescription is mathematically excluded by the non-overlap of the three running windows (top's lower bound exceeds charm's upper bound). All eight trials are computed and reported.

The result: of the eight trials, one closes. The combination $Q(c, b, t)$ with $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their tabulation self-scales and $m_c$ run via four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ to $\mu = m_\tau$ takes the value $0.666718$ against $2/3 = 0.666667$, a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$. The propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q$ is approximately $5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, dominated by the PDG uncertainty on $m_t$. The closure is approximately one order of magnitude below the input-precision band. The closure direction matches the literature near-miss direction (residual moves from $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ to $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, a sign change of the expected sense). The other seven trials --- charm at self-scale, charm at $\Sigma m_\ell$, bottom at self-scale, bottom at $M_W$, bottom at $M_Z$, bottom at $m_H$, and top at self-scale --- produce residuals between $-4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ and $+2.19 \times 10^{-2}$, two to three orders of magnitude away from closure.

To test whether the lepton-scale phenomenon extends to mixed-sector triples that algebraically interleave leptons and quarks, we additionally evaluated the Koide combination over $54$ such triples (every $(\ell_1, \ell_2, q)$ and $(\ell, q_1, q_2)$ combination with the quark masses evaluated at lepton-derived scales). \textbf{No mixed-sector triple closes.} The best of the $54$ has residual $+1.67 \times 10^{-3}$ against the nearest small rational, approximately $30\times$ farther from closure than the $(c, b, t)$ at $m_\tau$ result. The lepton-scale phenomenon is therefore not a generic feature of mixed-sector Koide combinations: it appears narrowly, at specific structural conditions, in two distinct forms across the present work and the companion note.

\smallskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Koide relation; heavy quark masses; constrained search; lepton-derived scales; numerical observation
\end{abstract}


\section{Background and Motivation}
\label{sec:intro}

The Koide relation \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide_lepton}
\end{equation}
holds for the charged lepton pole masses to a residual of $-6.16 \times 10^{-6}$, an empirical regularity for which no derivation is currently accepted. Extensions to the quark sector were initiated by Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} for the $(s, c, b)$ triple under a $-\sqrt{m_s}$ sign convention. The natural sign-positive heavy triple $(c, b, t)$, computed with all three masses at their respective $\overline{\text{MS}}$ self-scales (the standard tabulation convention used by FLAG \citep{FLAG2024} and PDG \citep{PDG2024}), gives
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\text{all self-scales}} \;=\; 0.6620198, \qquad \text{residual} \;=\; -4.65 \times 10^{-3},
\end{equation}
a known near-miss whose direction (residual negative, $Q$ below $2/3$) indicates that for the combination to close, $Q$ must increase. We refer to this throughout as the \emph{literature direction}: the sign of the required correction is determined by the published all-self-scales evaluation, not by exploration.

In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported that the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating charged-lepton Descartes configuration matches the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau \approx 1883$~MeV within current FLAG lattice precision. That observation involves a lepton-derived quantity matching a quark mass at a lepton-derived scale, and it raised a working hypothesis: \textbf{lepton-derived scales may enter quark-sector relations under specific structural conditions}. The present note tests this hypothesis on an independent quark-sector object --- the heavy Koide combination --- using a search procedure constructed before the calculation to satisfy three properties: it is enumerable, it is more restricted than conventional phenomenological scale choices, and the candidate set is determined mechanically rather than by author selection.

\section{Setup}
\label{sec:setup}

We work in the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme throughout. Inputs:

\begin{itemize}
\item $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$, \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$, \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV ($\overline{\text{MS}}$, derived from PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} $m_t^{\text{pole}} = 172.57 \pm 0.29$~GeV via the four-loop pole-to-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ conversion of \citep{Marquard2015} as implemented in \texttt{CRunDec})
\item $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ \citep{PDG2024}
\item $m_e = 0.5109989461$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6583755$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV \citep{PDG2024}
\item $M_W = 80.369$~GeV, $M_Z = 91.1876$~GeV, $m_H = 125.25$~GeV \citep{PDG2024}
\end{itemize}

All quark masses are $\overline{\text{MS}}$ throughout: a single mass-renormalization scheme, no mixing of schemes. The three masses are evaluated at three different RG points within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, the standard PDG/FLAG tabulation convention. Running between scales is performed via four-loop QCD using \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec}, with full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$ giving active-flavor regions $n_f \in \{3, 4, 5, 6\}$. The combination is
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)(\mu_c, \mu_b, \mu_t) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_c(\mu_c) + m_b(\mu_b) + m_t(\mu_t)}{\left(\sqrt{m_c(\mu_c)} + \sqrt{m_b(\mu_b)} + \sqrt{m_t(\mu_t)}\right)^2}.
\label{eq:Q_def}
\end{equation}
where $\mu_q$ is the RG point at which $m_q$ is evaluated within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.


\section{The Constrained-Search Rule and Trial Space}
\label{sec:rule}

\subsection{The rule}

We adopt the following search rule, stated before the calculation:
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Rule.} The RG point $\mu_q$ at which a heavy quark mass $m_q$ is evaluated within $\overline{\text{MS}}$ must be either (i)~the self-scale $m_q(m_q)$ of that quark, or (ii)~the mass of a Standard Model particle that lies within the perturbative running window of $m_q$.
\end{quote}
The perturbative running window of a heavy quark mass $m_q$ is the interval bounded by adjacent flavor thresholds: $[m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b)]$ for charm in the $n_f = 4$ region, $[m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)]$ for bottom in the $n_f = 5$ region, and $[m_t(m_t), \infty)$ for top in the $n_f = 6$ region. We require Standard Model particle scales (fermion or boson masses) and explicitly disallow round-number conventions ($1.5$~GeV, $2$~GeV, $\ldots$) which are tabulation conveniences rather than physical scales.

\subsection{Enumeration of the trial space}

Under this rule, we enumerate the trial space directly:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Top.} Running window $[m_t(m_t), \infty)$. No Standard Model particle has rest mass above $m_t$. Trial count for top: \textbf{one} (self-scale only).
\item \textbf{Bottom.} Running window $[m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)] = [4.20, 162.5]$~GeV. Standard Model particles in this window: $M_W = 80.369$~GeV, $M_Z = 91.188$~GeV, $m_H = 125.25$~GeV, plus the self-scale itself. Trial count for bottom: \textbf{four}.
\item \textbf{Charm.} Running window $[m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b)] = [1.28, 4.20]$~GeV. Standard Model particles in this window: $m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV and $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.88303$~GeV (the charged-lepton sum), plus the self-scale itself. Trial count for charm: \textbf{three}.
\end{itemize}

We test trials in which a single mass is varied from its self-scale to a candidate scale in its window; the other two masses are held at their respective self-scales. Total trial count: $\mathbf{1 + 4 + 3 = 8}$.

\subsection{Proof that the trial space is more restricted than the conventional phenomenological space}

\begin{proposition}
Let $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ denote the trial space defined above. Let $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$ denote the conventional phenomenological scale space, in which each heavy quark mass may be evaluated independently at any of the standard reference scales used in the heavy-quark mass literature: $\{m_c(m_c), 1.5 \mathrm{~GeV}, 2 \mathrm{~GeV}, m_b(m_b), m_\tau, \Sigma m_\ell, M_W, M_Z, m_H, m_t(m_t)\}$, ten options per mass. Then
\begin{equation}
|\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}| = 8 \;\;<\;\; |\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}| = 10^3 = 1000.
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
$|\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}| = 8$ by direct enumeration above. For $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$, each of the three masses may independently take any of ten scale values, giving $10^3 = 1000$ prescriptions. Containment $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}} \subset \mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$ holds trivially: every prescription in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ is also in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$, since (i) every running-window scale used in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ appears in the conventional list, and (ii) the constraint that at most one mass deviates from its self-scale is a strict additional restriction not imposed in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$. The containment is strict because, e.g., $\mathcal{S}_{\text{conv}}$ admits the prescription $(\mu_c = 2 \mathrm{~GeV}, \mu_b = m_b, \mu_t = m_t)$ which is not in $\mathcal{S}_{\text{this work}}$ ($2$~GeV is a tabulation convention, not a particle mass). \qed
\end{proof}

The trial space of this paper is therefore $125\times$ smaller than the conventional phenomenological space. The corresponding Bonferroni penalty is $8$, not $1000$.

\subsection{Proof that the common-scale prescription is mathematically excluded}

\begin{proposition}
There exists no scale $\mu \in \mathbb{R}_{>0}$ at which all three masses $m_c, m_b, m_t$ can be simultaneously evaluated within their respective perturbative running windows.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The three perturbative running windows are
\begin{align*}
W_c &= [m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b)] = [1.28, 4.20]~\text{GeV}, \\
W_b &= [m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)] = [4.20, 162.5]~\text{GeV}, \\
W_t &= [m_t(m_t), \infty) = [162.5, \infty)~\text{GeV}.
\end{align*}
A common scale $\mu$ for all three masses requires $\mu \in W_c \cap W_b \cap W_t$. We have $\sup W_c = 4.20$~GeV and $\inf W_t = 162.5$~GeV, with $4.20 < 162.5$, so $W_c \cap W_t = \emptyset$, and therefore $W_c \cap W_b \cap W_t = \emptyset$. \qed
\end{proof}

The common-scale prescription is therefore excluded by the non-overlap of the perturbative running windows, not by author choice. Empirically, if one extrapolates each mass outside its own perturbative window to a common $\mu$ (an unphysical procedure, since at least one mass is then evaluated outside the regime where its $\overline{\text{MS}}$ definition is reliable), the resulting combination $Q(c, b, t)$ is approximately constant at $0.7192$ across the entire perturbative range and never crosses $2/3$ at any scale. The common-scale extrapolation does not admit a closure even when permitted unphysically.


